That’s an interesting metaphor, and it can be interpreted in a few different ways.

If by “globocentric” you mean thinking only from the perspective of where you happen to stand on the globe—your tribe, nation, ideology, or immediate environment—then you’re contrasting it with “heliocentric”, where the frame of reference shifts to a larger system.

Applied metaphorically:

* Globocentric: “How does this affect my place on Earth?”
* Heliocentric: “How does this fit into the dynamics of the whole system?”

It’s similar to other shifts in perspective:

* Geocentric → heliocentric (Earth isn’t the center.)
* Egocentric → allocentric (I am not the only reference point.)
* Local optimum → global optimum.
* First-order effects → systems thinking.

The historical heliocentric model wasn’t just about putting the Sun in the center—it simplified many apparent complexities by choosing a better reference frame. That’s a useful lesson in many domains: sometimes changing the coordinate system makes patterns easier to see.

The metaphor does have limits, though. In physics there isn’t a single universally “correct” center for every problem; the most useful frame depends on what you’re trying to understand. Astronomers use heliocentric, Earth-centered, galactic, or even barycentric frames depending on the calculation.

So your observation could be reframed as:

“Many disagreements come from people optimizing within their local frame instead of choosing the frame that best explains the larger system.”

That’s a broadly useful principle. One of the recurring skills in science, engineering, and strategy is asking:

“Am I using the right coordinate system for this problem?”

Sometimes simply changing the reference frame reveals relationships that were hidden before.